# Section 1: Introduction & Philosophy (index.md)

## Introduction

HuskHoard is a **Hybrid User-Space Storage Kernel** designed to solve the "NVMe Capacity Gap." It provides transparent, automated data tiering for Linux, allowing you to treat slow, high-capacity storage (HDDs, Cloud Buckets) as a seamless extension of your high-speed SSD.

## The Problem

Modern storage is polarized.

- **NVMe SSDs** are incredibly fast but expensive and small.
- **Hard drives and Cloud storage** are cheap and massive but slow and cumbersome to manage.

Most users end up manually moving files back and forth, leading to **"Data Silos"** where files are forgotten or inaccessible.

## The HuskHoard Solution

HuskHoard automates this process using **Transparent Stubbing**.

**The Husk:** When a file gets "cold" (not accessed for a set time), HuskHoard moves the data to an archive volume and "punches a hole" in the original file on the SSD.

**The Transparency:** The file remains visible in your folders. It still shows its full size. You can still click it.

**The Recall:** When an application tries to read the file, HuskHoard intercepts the request, pulls the data back from the archive, and feeds it to the application in real-time.

## Our Philosophy

- **No Vendor Lock-in:** Your data is stored in standard Zstd-compressed streams with BLAKE3 checksums. If HuskHoard disappeared tomorrow, a simple Python script could extract your files.
- **Sequential-First:** We treat hard drives like tapes. By writing sequentially, we eliminate the performance "write-wall" of SMR drives and extend the life of your hardware.
- **User-Space Power:** By using the Linux fanotify API, we achieve the power of a kernel-level filesystem with the safety and ease of a user-space application.
